Review: Feels so good to be alive.
Wanted the fully immersive experience so I (quite unfortunately literally) totaled my car on my way to my first attempt at watching this. Sending Regal a pitch for my 5DX experience as we speak...
Man, this camrip sucks—bro can't even keep the camera pointed at the screen the whole time.
Good story bogged down by lifeless characters.
Think I'm finally ready to admit this is a perfect movie.
Never too late for some westcember. Doc Holliday has to be one of the coolest dudes of all time and that final shootout is everything a good western aspires to be.
All time great movie dad in this one.

I completely buy into the read that this is Fincher making so much fun of himself and it rules. Probably the best possible follow-up film you could make if you unfortunately found yourself to be the guy who directed Mank; not a misstep by any means.
Creating an L.A. neo-noir narrated by Joanna Newsom (with a score by Jonny Greenwood) is tantamount to cheating, man. My favorite Joaquin performance and Paul Thomas Anderson work by a country mile.

This film should absolutely collapse under its own weight and yet it never falters for an instant on its journey to transcendence. Its narrative could be summarized briefly as a combination of Spirited Away and The Wind Rises but that would also be a gross oversimplification; there's bits and pieces of every Miyazaki film in here and, in that manner, it rightfully serves as a culmination of everything his work has aimed to achieve over the decades.

Wasn't surprised at all that this might've single-handedly converted me into a Godzilla fun, but I was not expecting it to also make me a 4DX truther. Have little to no reference point for how this stands as a Godzilla movie but I liked the big lizard and I liked the human characters even more. Stunning final set piece, too.
